.NET Native Interop Performance Report¶

The following report evaluates the performance overhead of calling native C/C++ functions from managed C# code using the built-in interoperability capabilities of .NET known as P/Invoke. The report presents benchmarks of common interop scenarios that involve marshalling and passing values of primitive types, strings, arrays, and structures, in both directions (i.e. as both function parameters and return values or out parameters). Several ways of implementing the interop calls that have been added to the .NET framework throughout the years, namely the DllImport attribute, the source-generator backed LibraryImport attribute, and unmanaged function pointers are compared.

The benchmarks were executed on three .NET runtime versions as permitted by their respective supported feature sets: .NET Framework 4.8 (the last major version of the classic Windows-only runtime), .NET 6 (current LTS version of the portable .NET Core runtime) and the latest .NET 8 Preview.

1. Related work¶

To our knowledge, there are not many comparable studies publicly available.

  • This article compares performance of a single interop call implemented via DllImport, managed delegates and function pointers on .NET 5. It shows DllImport and function pointers to have comparable performance with the latter having ~1ns lesser overhead. Managed delegates are roughly twice as slow.
  • This article compares two interop scenarios implemented via DllImport, delegates and directly emitting the calli IL instruction. DllImport and the calli-based calls are shown to have similar performance with the latter being 1-2 ns faster. Delegates are almost two orders of magnitude slower in the measured scenarios. We opted not to include
  • There are also older articles (see and see) containing benchmarking results focused on particular comparisons between P/Invoke and C++/CLI interop.
  • The .NET runtime team maintains a public repository of benchmarks used to measure changes in performance between runtime versions, however, the benchmark suite does not include almost any interop-related scenarios.

2. Overview of P/Invoke¶

In this section we provide a brief introduction to the .NET capabilities covered by the report. We describe the basic interop concepts and several APIs for declaring interop calls available in .NET under the umbrella term P/Invoke (short for Platform Invocation Services).

2.1. Basic concepts and the DllImport attribute¶

The original P/Invoke API available since .NET 1.1 is using the DllImport attribute. This attribute is added to a declaration of a static extern (i.e. body-less) method like this:

[DllImport("kernel32.dll")]
public static extern bool QueryPerformanceCounter(out long counter);

Such method can be called from the user code as a regular C# method. However, its implementation is generated during run-time based on the method signature and the configuration provided in theDllImport attribute (and several related attributes). For example, for the declaration above the built-in interop service of the .NET runtime generates code that tries to load the kernel32.dll native library (using the standard OS dynamic library resolution mechanism), get the address of the QueryPerformanceCounter function in the library and calls it using special Intermediate Language instruction calli for calling unmanaged callsites.

The actual execution process is more complex and involves resolving a series of IL stubs (see). However, this is beyond the scope of this report. What is more important is that, depending on the method signature and the DllImport configuration, the call may also include several safety related operations (see Section 2.5.) and, more importantly, perform marshalling of the function's arguments and return value.

What happens during interop marshalling depends on whether the function's return value and arguments have blittable types or not. Data type is called blittable if it has the same representation in managed and unmanaged memory. Such types therefore do not need conversion when passed between .NET and native code. The following types are blittable:

  • Primitive types such as byte, int, float, and double.
  • Structs with fixed layout that contain only blittable fields (excluding array fields).
  • One-dimensional arrays of blittable types.

Primitive blittable arguments and return values can be passed on the stack or in registers as-is (depending on the calling convention). In the case of reference types (or value types passed as ref parameters) being blittable means that instead of copying the value to the unmanaged memory, a pointer to the value's location in the managed memory can be passed to the native code. This saves one copy for in parameters and up to two copies for out parameters.

Conversely, non-blittable types are types whose representation needs to be appropriately converted during interop. These types include:

  • char .NET characters are represented as 2-byte UTF-16 code units. By default, DllImport converts these to single-byte ANSI characters on Windows and UTF-8 characters on other platforms. The marshaller can be configured using attribute option to pass chars in the UTF-16 format.
  • string Strings need to be converted to null-terminated character arrays and passed as pointers. Similarly to individual characters, DllImport supports either UTF-16 or ANSI/UTF-8 strings.
  • bool Bools have historically multiple representations in different environments, ranging from 1 to 4 bytes, possibly with different mappings of numeric to boolean values. Attributes can be used to configure which format is used by the marshaller.
  • Arrays other than one-dimensional arrays of blittable types.
  • Structures and classes containing any non-blittable fields, including array fields (with the exception of blittable arrays with compile-time constant size)

For convenience, the built-in DllImport marshaller handles several common scenarios involving non-blittable types automatically. This includes passing strings and bools (with optional configuration as mentioned) and also handling out parameters whose value needs to be provided back to the caller (such as the out long counter parameter of the QueryPerformanceCounter method above). In more complex cases (e.g. when passing non-blittable structures) the marshalling needs to be done by the user manually.

2.2. Marshalling code generation and the LibraryImport attribute¶

Recently, the LibraryImport attribute has been added in .NET 7 as a replacement of DllImport for declaring P/Invoke methods. Apart from API changes that were made to remove the historical Windows-specific features and to unify the behavior on different platforms the most interesting difference is that the marshalling code (at least for non-trivial marshalling) is generated during compile-time instead of at run-time. This feature is enabled by the source generator mechanism which analyzes the user's code using the Roslyn compiler API and generates additional C# (not IL) code as part of the compilation (or on the fly in an IDE).

For example, when user declares a method such as:

struct Timespec
{
    public long tv_sec;
    public long tv_nsec;
}

[LibraryImport("libc", EntryPoint = "clock_gettime")]
private static partial int GetTime(int clk_id, ref Timespec tp);

Then the interop source generator provides the implementation of the partial method similar to this (code modified for readability):

private static partial int GetTime(int clk_id, ref Timespec tp)
{
    int __retVal;

    fixed (Timespec* __tp_native = &tp)
    {
        __retVal = __PInvoke(clk_id, __tp_native);
    }

    return __retVal;

    [DllImport("libc", EntryPoint = "clock_gettime")]
    static extern unsafe int __PInvoke(int clk_id, Timespec* tp);
}

Notice that the implementation internally still uses the DllImport attribute (and therefore the run-time interop service). However, the generated code handles non-trivial marshalling, in this case pinning the out parameter struct in memory and passing pointer to it to the native call. In this way the LibraryImport attribute converts the interop call to the which involves only passing primitive values on stack.

This has several ramifications for performance:

  • Any inherent overhead of DllImport pertaining to calling the native method (marshalling excluded) also applies to LibraryImport.
  • On the other hand, no run-time reflection and IL emission is needed to construct the marshalling code. This might lead to better cold start performance in particular.
  • The pre-generated marshalling code can be inlined already by the C# compiler, not just the JIT compiler.
  • The source generated interop is compatible with the Native AOT compilation available since .NET 7 (outside of the scope of this report).

2.3. Unsafe function pointers¶

.NET 5 added another way of calling native functions using function pointers. This involves manually loading the native library and acquiring address to the exported function using the NativeLibrary API. The address (represented as an untyped IntPtr handle) can than be in an unsafe context cast to a typed function pointer using a special delegate* syntax. This pointer can be then invoked as a regular C# function. For example:

IntPtr kernelLib = NativeLibrary.Load("kernel32.dll");
IntPtr qpcPtr = NativeLibrary.GetExport(kernelLib, "QueryPerformanceCounter");
unsafe
{
    var qpc = (delegate* unmanaged<out long, bool>)qpcPtr;
    bool isSuccess = qpc(out long timestamp);
}

There is a very little documentation on the internal implementation of interop via function pointers. Apparently (see discussion), the feature uses the same runtime interop service as traditional P/Invoke with DllImport, including basic marshalling capabilities. However, there is no support for marshalling most non-blittable types and the user is expected to convert any such values manually.

Without the knowledge of internals it is difficult to predict whether function pointers differ in performance from DllImport methods.

2.4. Other methods¶

We omit use of managed delegates as these have shown to be significantly slower (see Related work) while not providing benefits over the other methods. We also not included implementation based on emitting the calli IL instruction during run-time as we wanted to focus on more standard .NET APIs intended for general developer audience.

2.5. Interop settings¶

There are a few options available for DllImport and LibraryImport declarations that modify run-time behavior of the interop call. We evaluate effect of enabling or disabling these options in Section 5.2. Here we briefly describe their effect.

SetLastError¶

When the SetLastError attribute is added to the P/Invoke method declaration the marshaller retrieves the error code set by the called function (using GetLastError on Windows or errno on Linux) and stores it in a thread static variable for the managed code to use. Since .NET 5 the error variable is also cleared before each call. Enabling this option might incur minor performance overhead.

SuppressUnmanagedCodeSecurity¶

In the original .NET Framework each P/Invoke call involved a check for a permission to call unmanaged code (depending on the properties of the .NET assembly and the user that executed it). This check had to perform a stack walk to determine if the entire call chain conformed to the relevant security policy, causing a performance overhead for each interop call. This behavior can be disabled by adding the SuppressUnmanagedCodeSecurity attribute to the DllImport method declaration. The rewritten .NET Core abandoned the mechanism of Code Access Security and this attribute does nothing when executed on Core runtimes.

SuppressGCTransition¶

Each P/Invoke call causes the garbage collector to switch for the duration of the call from the default cooperative mode (where GC can only start once all threads reach a safe point) to the preemptive mode. This is done so that a blocking native call does not prevent GC for too long or indefinitely. Unsurprisingly, the mode switch incurs an performance overhead for each interop call.

The SuppressGCTransition attribute, which was previously used only internally in .NET base libraries and has been made available to users in .NET 5, allows to skip the GC mode transition. It should be noted, however, that this option is safe to use only for a restricted class of interop calls (see list of conditions).

3. Benchmark platform¶

All tests were performed on a desktop computer with the following hardware and software specifications.

Hardware platform

  • CPU: Intel Core i5 10400F, 6 physical cores, 12 hyper-threads, running at fixed 2900 MHz frequency
  • RAM: 64 GB DDR4, running at 3200 Mhz frequency
  • Storage: Samsung 970 1 TB NVMe SSD

Operation system

  • Windows 10 22H2 (Build 19045.3448)

.NET SDKs

  • .NET Framework 4.8
  • .NET 6.0.414
  • .NET 8.0.100-preview.7.23376.3

C++ compiler

  • g++ 13.2.0 (MSYS distribution)
  • Compiler options: -std=c++17 -O2 -Wall

4. Plotting scripts¶

The following code is used throughout the report to plot the benchmark results.

In [1]:
import glob
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import sys

color_map = dict(zip(
    ["Managed", "DllImport", "LibraryImport", "FuncPointers"],
    ["#79ccb3","#e9724d", "#d6d727", "#92cad1", ]
))

order_map = dict(zip(
    ["Managed", "DllImport", "LibraryImport", "FuncPointers"],
    [10, 20, 30, 40]
))


def load_results_file(run_dir: str) -> pd.DataFrame:
    results_dir = run_dir + "/results"
    file = glob.glob(results_dir + "/*measurements.csv")[0]
    df = pd.read_csv(file, delimiter=";")
    return df

def merge_results_files(root_dir: str) -> pd.DataFrame:
    files = glob.glob(root_dir + "*/results/*measurements.csv")
    result = pd.DataFrame()
    for file in files:
        df = pd.read_csv(file, delimiter=";")
        result = pd.concat([result, df])
    return result

def make_barplot(input_df: pd.DataFrame, title, unit, category = None, param = None, figsize = (14, 6)):
    category_df = input_df if category is None else input_df.query(f"Category == '{category}'")
    param_df = category_df if param is None else category_df.query(f"Params == '{param}'")
    grouped_df = param_df.groupby(["Target_Type", "Target_Method", "Job_Runtime"])

    items = []
    methods = {
        ".NET 4.8": set(),
        ".NET 6.0": set(),
        ".NET 8.0": set(),
    }

    for keys, data in grouped_df:
        (type, method, runtime) = keys
        runtime_version = ".NET " + runtime.split(" ")[-1]
        case = f"{type}-{method}"
        methods[runtime_version].add(case)

        method_parts = method.split("_")
        bar = type if len(method_parts) < 2 else f"{type}\n({method_parts[-1]})"
        color_map[bar] = color_map[type]

        for val in data["Measurement_Value"].to_list():
            items.append({
                "Type": bar,
                "Runtime": runtime_version,
                "Value": val if unit == "ns" else val / 1000.0 / 1000.0,
                "Order": order_map[type],
                "Color": color_map[type]
            })

    items.sort(key=lambda x: x["Order"])

    method_total = sum(map(len, methods.values()))
    method_ratios = list(filter(lambda x: x > 0, map(lambda x: len(x) / method_total, methods.values())))
    
    used_runtimes = list(filter(lambda kv: len(kv[1]) > 0, methods.items()))
    runtime_plot_info = list(zip(used_runtimes, range(0, len(used_runtimes))))

    input_df = pd.DataFrame(items)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, len(runtime_plot_info), figsize=figsize, sharey=True, gridspec_kw={'width_ratios': method_ratios})
    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=16, fontweight="bold")
    fig.supylabel(f"Mean execution time ({unit})", fontsize=12)

    for ((runtime, mets), i) in runtime_plot_info:
        _df = input_df[input_df.Runtime == runtime]
        plot = sns.barplot(
            ax=ax[i],
            data=_df,
            x="Type", y="Value",
            palette=color_map,
            saturation=1.0
        )

        if method_total > 10:
            plot.set_xticklabels(plot.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, fontsize=9)

        ax[i].bar_label(ax[i].containers[0], fmt='%.2f', label_type="center")
        ax[i].set_xlabel("")
        ax[i].set_ylabel("")
        ax[i].set_title(runtime, fontsize=12)

    plt.show()

5. Experiments¶

We implemented the benchmarks using the BenchmarkDotNet library which is the de-facto standard for micro-benchmarking .NET code. The library provides API for declaring benchmark jobs (similarly to unit testing frameworks), handles benchmark execution and exporting results. When executing a benchmark in BenchmarkDotNet, the harness builds a separate .NET project for each combination of runtime environment, job definition and job parameters, and then performs a series of stages intended to ensure meaningful results based on steady state performance. In particular:

  • Pilot iterations are used to select proper number of operations to do per actual benchmark iteration. The library uses configurable heuristics to compute this number (e.g. target iteration length or target error). We configured the library to select operation count such that the results from Pilot iterations have relative error (defined as <half of CI 99.9%> / mean) less than 0.01.
  • Overhead iterations (warmup and workload) are used to estimate overhead of the benchmark runner itself. Mean of this value is later subtracted from the actual results.
  • Warmup iterations are used to warmup the actual workload method.
  • Workload iterations are used to measure the actual benchmark results.

This worklfow describes the standard throughput benchmarks that comprise majority of this report. In Section 5.7. we also try to evaluate the cold start performance. To do so, we execute benchmarks using configuration that disables the previously described stages. Instead it simply performs some number of separate launches, each with one iteration and one operation executed. No warmup or overhead estimation is done in this configuration.

All the measured data presented in the report can be found int ReportData directory. There you can also find for each benchmark category a summary of the results (including more statistical measures than presented in the report) such as this:

5.1. Overhead baseline¶

To establish the overhead of calling the very minimal native function lets first evaluate calls to an empty parameterless void function.

// C# signature
static void Empty();

// C++ function
void Empty() {}

The following figure (and other such figures in the report) shows the mean execution time of calling the native function using the different interop APIs. Not all APIs are available on all evaluated runtimes:

  • .NET Framework 4.8 supports only DllImport.
  • .NET 6 supports DllImport and function pointers.
  • .NET 8 supports DllImport, LibraryImport and function pointers.

Execution time of a semantically equivalent C# method is added as a baseline. The method (and other such C# methods in the report) is set to not be inlined using the MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.NoInlining) attribute. I have experimentally confirmed that this attribute is respected even for empty-bodied methods.

According to the official documentation, P/Invoke call is supposed to add about 10-30 x86 instructions compared to regular managed call. Estimating IPC of CPU for a given workload (more so for a mostly unknown one) is a difficult task, however, on a ~3 GHz modern CPU we would expect the interop call to have an overhead compared to the native call in the ballpark of 1-20 ns.

As there is no data marshalling involved, we expect all three interop APIs to perform close to identically.

In [2]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Void_Empty_2023-09-21T17_40_59")
make_barplot(data, "void Empty()", "ns")

Based on the results, the empty interop call has a base overhead of about 10 ns on .NET 4.8 runtime and about 6 ns on Core runtimes (on this particular computer). The solution with function pointers seem to be slightly faster than the others, possibly because it uses a stored pointer to the native method directly, rather than resolving it from some internal cache of the interop service as could be the case (this is a speculation) by the DllImport (and consequently LibraryImport) solutions.

5.2. Effect of interop settings¶

Section 2.5. indtroduced three safety or security related options with likely consequences for performance of the interop calls. Here we evaluate this effect.

SetLastError¶

We expect enabling the option to have minor negative effect on performance as additional work is needed for setting the thread-local value after the call and (on Core runtimes) clearing it before the call.

Bars labeled (SLE) have the option enabled, other have it disabled.

In [3]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/SLE_2023-09-21T15_09_58")
make_barplot(data, "SetLastError", "ns")

As shown, the option does an overhead ranging from about 6 ns (on .NET 4.8) to almost 10 ns (on .NET 8). The smaller performance hit on the older runtime is consistent with the fact that .NET 4.8 does not clear the value before the call.

SuppressUnmanagedCodeSecurity¶

We expect enabling the option to have a moderate positive effect on perfomance on .NET 4.8 and no effect on the newer runtimes.

Bars labeled (SUCS) have the option enabled, other have it disabled.

In [4]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/SUCS_2023-09-21T17_56_05")
make_barplot(data, "SuppressUnmanagedCodeSecurity", "ns")

As expected the option does entail a performance improvement on .NET 4.8, cutting the cost of the empty interop call by third. On Core runtimes there seems to be, somewhat surprisingly, very small performance improvement as well.

We observed previously that the base performance overehad of interop calls on the old runtime is relatively higher compared to the Core runtimes. This indicates that the difference is largely due to the security stack walk performed by default on .NET Framework which is not implemented at all by the Core runtimes.

SuppressGCTransition¶

We expect enabling the option to measurably reduce the base call overhead of the interop methods. Note that the option is only available since .NET 5.

Bars labeled (SGCT) have the option enabled, other have it disabled.

In [5]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/SGCT_2023-09-21T17_54_04")
make_barplot(data, "SuppressGCTransition", "ns")

We observed improvement in performance by about 45% on .NET 6 and 35% on .NET 8.

Note, however, that more complex benchmark scenarios would be needed to properly evaluate the effect of disabling the GC mode transition during interop calls - e.g. in a GC intensive multi-threaded scenario.

5.3. Marshalling primitive types¶

Before examining more complex types lets consider a simple case of passing primitive arguments and return values. We will use the following functions:

// C# signatures
static int MultiplyInt(int a, int b);
static bool NegateBool(bool value);

// C++ functions
int MultiplyInt(int a, int b) { return a * b; }
bool NegateBool(bool value) { return !value; }

The MultiplyInt function represents a straightforward call with blittable parameters and return value. We expect this function to perform similarly to the empty void function.

The NegateBool function is more interesting as bool is actually not a blittable type due to possible differences in representation between .NET and the native code. By default, DllImport marshalls boolean values as 4-byte integers (due to WinAPI tradition). The benchmarked code specifies that bool values should be marshalled as single unsigned byte values with 1 representing true and 0 representing false. As such we expect to see small performance hit compared to the blittable MultiplyInt method.

In [6]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Primitive_Int_InOut_2023-09-21T06_53_12")
make_barplot(data, "int MultiplyInt(int, int)", "ns")
In [7]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Primitive_Bool_InOut_2023-09-21T06_56_50")
make_barplot(data, "bool NegateBool(bool)", "ns")

The MultiplyInt call seems to be about 2.5 ns slower comapared the Empty void function. The NegateBool function shows some differences based on the interop API used. The LibraryImport solution seems to be measurably slower (even relatively to DllImport), perhaps due to some inefficiency of the generated marshalling code. Meanwhile the function pointer solution with a handwritten marshalling is faster than the others.

5.4. Marshalling dynamic arrays¶

Arrays in .NET are dynamically sized (i.e. the size is not baked into the type in compile-time). Therefore, they need to be passed to native functions as pointers along with the size of the array that the funcion can safely operate on.

Moreover, when passing dynamically sized buffer the representation in managed memory needs to be either copied in/out via unmanaged memory, or it needs to be protected from being moved by GC. In the benchmarked scenarios we experiment with the two most common ways of accessing managed memory in native code directly - the unsafe fixed operator and pinning via the Marshal API.

These methods are used like this:

var managedArray = new int[100];

// Method 1: Copying data in (and out) via unmanaged heap
IntPtr ptr = Marshal.AllocCoTaskMem(sizeof(int) * managedArray.Length);
Marshal.Copy(managedArray, 0, ptr, managedArray.Lentgth);
// 'ptr' can be passed to native code.
// Data needs to be copied back if it should be available to managed code.
Marshal.FreeCoTaskMem(ptr);

// Method 2: Unsafe pointer to fixed memory
unsafe {
    fixed (int* ptr = managedArray) {
        // 'ptr' can be passed to native code.
        // Data of managedArray can be accessed directly.
    }
}

// Method 3: Pinned handle
GCHandle handle = GCHandle.Alloc(managedArray, GCHandleType.Pinned);
IntPtr ptr = handle.AddrOfPinnedObject();
// 'ptr' can be passed to native code.
// Data of managedArray can be accessed directly.
handle.Free();

To evaluate performance when marshalling strings we use the following functions.

// C# signatures
static int SumIntArray(int[] arr, int count);
static void FillIntArray(int[] arr, int count);

// C++ functions
int SumIntArray(const int *arr, int count) {
    int acc = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < count; i++) {
        acc += arr[i];
    }
    return acc;
}

void FillIntArray(int *arr, int count) {
    for (int i = 0; i < count; i++) {
        arr[i] = i;
    }
}

Note that SumIntArray uses the array only as an in parameter. For this scenario we use the fact that for blittable arrays (such as arrays of ints) this work can be done under the hood by the marshaller. This enables writing interop method declarations that simply take a regular C# array as a parameter (in the case of DllImport and LibraryImport).

We benchmark the SumIntArray call using arrays with 10 and 1000 items. We expect the function pointer based solution and LibraryImport to be on par. Code for the first is handwritten and code for the latter can inspected after generation. DllImport is hard to predict but probably does a similiar fixing/pinning of the array memory under the hood. We expect any possible difference between the solution gets lower with larger array as the execution time get dominated by the native function itself.

In [8]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Arrays_In_2023-09-21T07_00_28")
make_barplot(data, "int SumIntArray(const int*, int) with 10 items", "ns", param="input=Int32[10]")
In [9]:
make_barplot(data, "int SumIntArray(const int*, int) with 1000 items", "ns", param="input=Int32[1000]")

As expected the three interop solutions performed very similarly, especially for the larger input. Interestingly, in .NET 4.8 and .NET 6 the managed implementation (which is implemented using an equivalent for loop and a counter) is for the larger input signitficantly slower then the interoped native calls. This indicates some interesting optimization in .NET 8 which causes it to have almost exactly the same performance as the native versions.

The second evaluated function FillIntArray writes its output to it as an out parameter. We experimented with more ways of marshalling the array in and out of the native call. These variants are labeled in the figure below as such:

  • ByValue - The same automatically marshalled approach as used for SumIntArray.
  • Fixed - A pointer to the array in managed memory is acquired in a fixed block. The pointer is passed to the native function. (See Method 2 above.)
  • Pinned - A pinned GCHandle for the array in managed memory is acquired. A pointer protected by the handle is passed to the native function. (See Method 3 above.)

We expect the ByValue and Fixed variants to behave similarly as it seems to be the case that the built-in marshallers use fixed pointers to pass managed arrays to native code. The Pinned variant is hard to predict, however, due to the added safety it is supposed to bring, we would expect some additional overhead compared to the Fixed variant.

In [10]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Arrays_InOut_2023-09-21T14_52_09")
make_barplot(data, "void FillIntArray(int *, int) with 10 items", "ns", param="input=Int32[10]")
In [11]:
make_barplot(data, "void FillIntArray(int *, int) with 1000 items", "ns", param="input=Int32[1000]")

From the results it is obvious that pinned references have a much higher base performance cost than fixed pointers. However, this overhead is much less significant when dealing with larger arrays.

As with the previous method, .NET 8 displays some intereseting optimization in the Managed implementation.

It should be noted that frequent and/or long-lasting pinning or fixing of objects causes problems for the GC and leads to heap fragmentation. It is therefore likely to have a detrimental effect on overall performance which might not be evident from simple benchmarks like this.

5.5. Marshalling strings¶

Marshalling strings involves dealing with the following two problems. First, general strings are fundamentally dynamically sized arrays of characters and share the same problems as arrays during interop. More importanly, strings have historically a multitude of representations.

Strings in .NET are represented as objects containing an array of UTF-16 characters and an explicit Length property. In C, strings are traditionally represented as null-terminated char * arrays. (The C++ std::string is for many reasons, most of them outside of the Earthly scope of this report, unusable for interop scenarios). Passing .NET strings to native functions using char * therefore requires allocating the necessary buffer and converting the string to a compatible representation (ASCII, ANSI, UTF-8). Unmarshalling string from a native code requires a symmetric conversion. Just like with arrays, the pointer to the string buffer can be either a pointer to an unmanaged heap, a pinned GCHandle or a fixed unsafe pointer.

To evaluate performance when marshalling strings we use the following functions.

// C# signatures
static int StringLength8(string str);
static int StringLength16(string str);
static string StringToUppercase(string str);

// C++ functions
int StringLength8(const char *str) { return (int)strlen(str); }

int StringLength16(const char16_t *str) { return (int)std::char_traits<char16_t>::length(str); }

void StringToUppercase(char *str, int length) {
    for (int i = 0; i < length; i++) {
        str[i] = toupper(str[i]);
    }
}

Note that StringLength8 and StringLength16 only use the string as an in parameter. The first requires conversion to an 8-bit char representation, while the latter expects 16-bit characters. We expect the 16-bit variant to have reduced marshalling overhead due to not needing to convert the character representation.

In [12]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Strings_In_2023-09-21T16_01_42")
make_barplot(data, "int StringLength(const char/char16_t *)", "ns")

It is clear that converting from UTF-16 to UTF-8 representation adds non-trivial overhead to the interop call. Meanwhile, marshalling UTF-16 strings with LibraryImport and function pointer is only slightly slower than calling a method with integer arguments. This is again due to the fact that no memory buffer is allocated or copied, but a fixed pointer is passed to the native code. The noticable bad performance of the UTF-8 function pointer variant is due to it using the Marshal.StringToCoTaskMemUTF8 methods to acquire a safe pointer. This method actually copies the string content to a separate buffer.

Unlike the StringLength functions, the StringToUppercase function uses its char * argument as both in and out parameter. This means that some marshalling work is required in both directions.

The following figure compares performance between several possible C# implementations of the native interface.

  • ByteArray - String is converted to byte[] of UTF-8 characters, then passed to the marshaller as a blittable array. After the native call, the content of the array is converted to a .NET string.
  • Fixed - String is converted to byte[] array of UTF-8 characters, then a fixed pointer to the array in managed memory is passed to the native function. After the native call, the content of the array is converted to a .NET string.
  • SringBuilder - Variant only available with DllImport marshalling which handles passing StringBuilder as special pattern for returning string from the native code. Passes pointer to the mutable internal StringBuilder buffer which the native code can write into. The written value can then be retrieved using the standard .ToString() method.

We expect the ByteArray and Fixed variants to have very similar performance in the case that the marshaller internally converts the former variant to the letter (which at least the LibraryImport generator does). The StringBuilder variant is hard to predcit, but we would expect it to perform somewhat worse as it is using a fairly complex class just to get a contiguous memory buffer that can be passed via pointer to the native code. The same thing is done in the other variants (supposedly for some of them) as well, and in a more straightforward manner.

In [13]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Strings_InOut_2023-09-21T07_26_08")
make_barplot(data, "void StringToUppercase(char *, int)", "ns")

The results show a rather balanced performance across the tested variants. This confirms the expectations about resolving to the same internal marshalling implementation. The StringBuilder solution is also measurably slower, albeit much less so on .NET 4.8. (This makes some sense as it was the recommended solution in .NET Framework times, while it is not even supported by the new LibraryImport API.)

5.6. Marshalling structures¶

Marshalling structures (and classes with sequential layout) differ considerably for blittable and non-blittable structures. The first on can be handled as any primitve type and passed around on stack without special marshalling. Non-blittable structures on the other hand require conversion of all non-blittable fields before being passed to the native code. This typically involves replacing types such as arrays or strings with pointers, possibly requiring adding length fields for the pointed buffers.

We benchmark both a blittable and a non-blittable scenario. We use the following types and functions for this purpose.

// C# structures
public struct BlittableStruct
{
    public int a;
    public int b;
    public int result;
}

public struct NonBlittableStruct
{
    public int number;
    public bool flag;
    public string text;
    public int[] numberArray;
}

// C# signatures
static BlittableStruct SumIntsInStruct_Return(BlittableStruct input);
static void SumIntsInStruct_Ref(ref BlittableStruct input);
void UpdateNonBlittableStruct(ref MarshalledNonBlittableStruct input);

// C++ structures
struct BlittableStruct {
    int32_t a;
    int32_t b;
    int32_t result;
};

struct NonBlittableStruct {
    int32_t number;
    int32_t numberArraySize;
    int32_t *numberArray;
    char *text;
    bool flag;
};

// C++ functions
BlittableStruct SumIntsInStruct_Return(BlittableStruct data) {
    data.result = data.a + data.b;
    return data;
}

void SumIntsInStruct_Pointer(BlittableStruct *data) {
    data->result = data->a + data->b;
}

void UpdateNonBlittableStruct(NonBlittableStruct *data) { /* We omit function body for brevity */ }

First we will evaluate the methods working with blittable structures. The SumIntsInStruct_Return function takes a blittable structure by value and returns the updated copy of the structure as a return value. The SumIntsInStruct_Pointer procedure instead updates the input structure passed in as a pointer. As the structure is small and neither case involves any data conversions and heap allocations (local structs in C# are allocated on the stack), we expect the performance to be similar to MultiplyInt function in Section 5.3. The value returning variant might be slightly faster then the reference one due to better locality.

In [14]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Structs_Blittable_2023-09-21T07_29_37")
make_barplot(data, "BlittableStruct SumIntsInStruct_Return(BlittableStruct)\nvoid SumIntsInStruct_Pointer(BlittableStruct *)", "ns")

The expectation that the interop calls will behave as with the other primitive type functions was confirmed.

The final scenario which involves marshalling a more complex non-blittable struct is particular in that none of the interop APIs is able to provide automatic marshalling for the type. Therefore, we need to convert the structure to a fully-blittable one manually first, then we can pass it to the marshaller as in the previous case. The code we use for manual marshalling is identical across the three solutions, therefore we do not expect signifacnt performance differences. The only exception is a variant using the ability of the LibraryImport declarations to spcecify custom marshllers for the parameter/return value types. We implemented such custom marshaller for the NonBlittableStruct type.

However, due to the stateless design of the custom marshallers this implementation cannot use techniques such as memory pinning to optimize the native call. Instead, array or string fields require transfer buffers to be allocated and copied into when converting the structure to a blittable one. When the native call returns the data needs to be unmarshalled (copied) back to a new instance of the managed non-blittable structure. There are a good reasons for such design, mainly that it means that the marshaller can be used safely in any context. However, we expect the performance to be worse than with optimized manual marshalling.

In [15]:
data = load_results_file("ReportData/Throughput/Structs_NonBlittable_2023-09-21T07_36_59")
make_barplot(data, "void UpdateNonBlittableStruct(NonBlittableStruct *)", "ns")

All of the variants take significantly longer then the blittable case. The custom marshaller implementation has been proven to be approximately four times as slow as manual marshalling.

5.7. Cold start performance¶

In the previous sections we examined the average throughput performance of various interop calls. In this section we look at differences in the cold start performance of programs using the different interop APIs. By cold start performance we mean the time it takes to execute a method for the first time, including the JIT compilation, IL generation and other initial operations. This metric is interesting in particular when comparing DllImport based on run-time IL code generation and the new LibraryImport solution based on compile-time C# source generation.

The expectation is that pregenerating the marshalling code should lead to measurably faster cold start times. This should be the case for the function pointer solution as well, however, that one uses mostly handwritten (and error prone) marshalling code which reduces its usefulness for developers.

We estimated the cold start performance by sequentially executing 50 completely separate runs of the benchmark harness, each performing exactly one iteration with one invocation of the benchmarked method (for each configured runtime platform), with no warmup and overhead deduction. The following figures then present mean times across these runs.

With exception of the non-blittable structure case the LimbraryImport solution (and the function pointer one) is actually faster to start than the DllImport one, by about 30%. The non-blittable case seems to be hard to improve by compile-time generation as all the non-trivial marshalling code needed to be handwritten anyway for all three variants. It is, however, a bit weird that the LibraryImport start time is actually worse in this case.

It should be noted that the difference might get more significant for code bases with larger number of interop declarations.

6. Summary¶

Runtime versions¶

The results show that there have been a number of performance improvements between the old .Net Framework 4.8 runtime and the modern Core runtimes, with .NET 6 being on average 27.2% faster than .NET 4.8 in corresponding jobs. There are smaller performance differences between .NET 6 and .NET 8 runtimes in the benchmarked interop scenarios. The latest runtime was on average 11% percent faster.

Interop methods¶

Generally, we observed mostly minor throughput performance differences between the three solutions when running on the same runtime. This seems consistent with the fact that they only differ in marshalling of certain types, and internally use the same runtime interop service. On .NET 8, LibraryImport methods were on average 7.8% faster than corresponding DllImport methods. Function pointer based methods were on average 2.6% faster than LibraryImport methods, albeit requiring more handwritten code to implement.

We noticed that the design of the new custom marshaller API for LibraryImport seems to make it impossible to avoid copying data in/out by passing pointers to managed memory, which makes it significantly less efficient for marshalling non-blittable types than hand-written code.

We observed that using LibraryImport instead of DllImport improved cold start time (i.e. first method execution including JIT) in the benchmark scenarios with automatic marshalling by 23.2%. It closely matched performance of the solution based on function pointers which uses only handwritten code.

Interop settings¶

We observed the following effects of the available security options:

  • Enabling SetLastError adds a performance overhead of about 6 ns on .NET 4.8 and 10 ns on Core runtimes (up to 30% and 60% differnce, respectively, to baseline methods).
  • Enabling SuppressUnamangedCodeSecurity (i.e. disabling security stack walk) improves performance by about 4 ns on .NET Framework (30% difference to baseline).
  • Enabling SuppressGCTransition (i.e. disabling switching GC mode) improves performance by about 2.5 ns (45% difference to baseline).

Takeways¶

  • Simple calls with blittable types are not going to be performance issue unless they are done in very hot code paths. Even than they can be optimized by disabling some safet features, down to a single digit nanosecond overhead.
  • Generally, if performance is important when doing individual interop calls, using non-blittable types needs to be avoided as the cost of marshalling surpasses any other cause of inefficiency. As always, if the native API allows to offload significant work with few interop calls, cost of an individual interop call is not important.
  • If possible, using UTF-16 strings on the native side significantly alleviates the cost of marshalling .NET strings.
  • LibraryImport is at this point not a performance optimization but it provides better, less blackbox-like developer experience. There also seem to be opportunities for generating more optimized code with the source generator.
